title: SpaceX to launch first Starlink v2 satellites as part of doubleheader
summary: SpaceX is on tap this Monday for the first of two Starlink launches this week from each coast of the United States. The first one is the launch of the Starlink Group 6-1 mission which is scheduled to occur at 6:13 PM EST (23:13 UTC) from Space Launch Complex 40 (SLC-40) at the Cape Canaveral Space Force Station in Florida.

title: Technical issue scrubs SpaceX commercial crew launch
summary: A last-minute problem with a rocket ignition system halted a Falcon 9 launch of a NASA commercial crew mission Feb. 27, delaying the launch by at least three days.

title: China unveils lunar lander to put astronauts on the moon
summary: China has revealed a concept for a lunar lander it hopes will put astronauts on the moon around the end of the decade.

title: NASA SpaceX Set March 2 For Next Crew-6 Launch Attempt
summary: NASA and SpaceX are now targeting Thursday, March 2nd at 12:34am EST for the next launch attempt of Crew 6.

title: SpaceX, NASA scrub international Crew-6 launch to Station
summary: SpaceX and NASA scrubbed a launch of four people to the International Space Station (ISS) due to an issue with the TEA-TEB system that is used to light the engines. The launch director called a hold with just minutes remaining in the countdown.

title: Shortly before liftoff, SpaceX cancels a crew launch due to igniter issues
summary: "Standing down from tonight's launch of Crew-6 due to a TEA-TEB ground system issue."

title: NASA SpaceX Crew 6 Launch Aborted
summary: NASA SpaceX Crew 6's launch countdown has been halted and launch scrubbed due to an issue with TEA-TEB.

title: The Spaceport Company To Develop Commercial Sea Launch Pads
summary: The Spaceport Company, a startup founded by Tom Marotta, is proposing a solution to the increasing congestion at major launch sites: mobile launch pads that operate at sea.

title: SpaceX unveils next-gen Starlink V2 Mini satellites ahead of Monday launch

title: Startup developing sea-based launch pads
summary: A startup is proposing one solution to the increasing congestion at major launch sites: build mobile launch pads that operate at sea.
